## ⚠️ The most common procedural trap

The most common trap is simple:

People do not realize they are already inside a structured environment until after they have made unstructured decisions.

They assume:

- a phone call is enough
- a conversation counts as proof
- an explanation will substitute for documentation
- fairness will correct the process on its own
- silence means nothing is happening

Then they discover too late that:

- the file was never logged
- the deadline ran anyway
- the wrong department handled the issue
- no formal request was made
- the system only recognizes what entered the record

That is the trap.

Not ignorance of the law in the abstract.

Ignorance of the procedure already governing the moment.

